04833nam a22006255i 9780801462207DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014622077 a10.7591/97808014622072doi  a(DE-B1597)489607  a(OCoLC)1024044815  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aGardner, Andrew M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCity of Strangers :bGulf Migration and the Indian Community in Bahrain /cAndrew M. Gardner. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b13 halftones, 1 line drawing, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Pearls, Oil, and the British Empire -- t3. Foreign Labor in Peril -- t4. Strategic Transnationalism -- t5. The Public Sphere -- t6. Contested Identities, Contested Positions -- t7. The Invigorated State -- t8. Conclusion -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aIn City of Strangers, Andrew M. Gardner explores the everyday experiences of workers from India who have migrated to the Kingdom of Bahrain. Like all the petroleum-rich states of the Persian Gulf, Bahrain hosts an extraordinarily large population of transmigrant laborers. Guest workers, who make up nearly half of the country's population, have long labored under a sponsorship system, the kafala, that organizes the flow of migrants from South Asia to the Gulf states and contractually links each laborer to a specific citizen or institution.In order to remain in Bahrain, the worker is almost entirely dependent on his sponsor's goodwill. The nature of this relationship, Gardner contends, often leads to exploitation and sometimes violence. Through extensive observation and interviews Gardner focuses on three groups in Bahrain: the unskilled Indian laborers who make up the most substantial portion of the foreign workforce on the island; the country's entrepreneurial and professional Indian middle class; and Bahraini state and citizenry. He contends that the social segregation and structural violence produced by Bahrain's kafala system result from a strategic arrangement by which the state insulates citizens from the global and neoliberal flows that, paradoxically, are central to the nation's intended path to the future.City of Strangers contributes significantly to our understanding of politics and society among the states of the Arabian Peninsula and of the migrant labor phenomenon that is an increasingly important aspect of globalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aEast IndiansxViolence againstzBahrain. 0aEast IndianszBahrain. 0aForeign workers, East IndianxViolence againstzBahrain. 0aForeign workers, East IndianzBahrain. 4aAfrican Hist & Diaspora. 4aAnthropology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z97831106387210 cprintz978080144882940uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9780801462207?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801462207zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801462207/original  a978-3-11-053615-7 Cornell University P